As I have told other COVID-19 researchers, in my area (rural Georgia, USA), only those who are ill enough to be considered for hospital admission are being tested for COVID-19.  This means that many (myself included) are simply dealing with the "severe upper respiratory infection" symptoms at home and are NOT being tested or counted.  The numbers for infection are, I personally believe, very erroneous in the USA due to lack of testing supplies.  We simply have been staying in our homes and helping each other by delivering supplies and medicine to front porches.

We have made mask covers, homemade PPE face shields, and shields to cover the faces of COVID patients in ICU in order to protect the nurses and doctors. (This last request was from my niece, an ICU nurse, after having protected herself during a patient intubation with a plastic TRASH BAG)  We have delivered food to the hospital, to the elderly and to sick neighbors.

It's also difficult because I have an autoimmune disease and so I feel especially vulnerable and worried about getting sick. Hello there I think the most overwhelming for me is the idea that my 80 yr old grandmother is at risk as well as my mother. My grandmother because of her age (She's currently staying with my aunt because my uncle who normally hoses her was to paranoid and anxious about her getting sick with him as he works in a factory that was mandated to stay open). My mother is in her early fifties but she has kidney cancer, diabetes, And asthma that occasionally requires a nebulizer, She's also a smoker, has a bleeding disorder, and doesn't have a spleen. Her surgery to remove her cancer was canceled because of the pandemic. When I talk to her she also seems to not want to isolate as much as possible but rather goes to get cigarettes every other day and goes to get household goods or groceries a few times a week. It all feels very out of control and it's difficult for me to understand logically why these people who are such high risk because of age or comorbidities seem to rebuff the most stringent guidelines of protection more like the ability to see how they're putting themselves and us at risk.

This has been a nightmare that I feel I have been particularly ill-informed about. Just even the duration of stuff, and the lack of work. I have a freelance revenue stream that I thought I would be able to rely on when the restaurant I tend bar at (and manage the front of the house) closed. I was imagining a month. "I can do this for a month, it's not like I won't get any projects." I've gotten perhaps one tenth of the projects I normally get. That's right, for my part-time side-gig, the one that I spend maybe 25 hours a week doing, I've been getting maybe two and a half hours worth of work.
My boyfriend lost all of his hours at the hotel he works at. We have effectively $50 a week coming in right now, in a situation where we were living not quite paycheck to paycheck, but we sure are happy when we get paid. I donated a decent amount of money to the Red Cross three weeks ago, maybe four. I felt like I would he helping. I wanted people with less than I have to not be totally screwed. In doing that, I screwed myself badly. 
I don't know why I thought this wouldn't take a long time to sort out. My sister is an ICU nurse. I've been getting information from her. She has a better idea than I do (obviously) and her opinions aren't clouded by politics. SDhe said to plan on a month, maybe a month and a half AT A MINIMUM. I didn't hear the AT A MINIMUM part, or maybe I blocked it out. We're totally screwed. We've filed for unemployment two weeks ago. Their office is amazingly understaffed right now.
